## 13. COMMON MISTAKES TO AVOID

### Language Mistakes

- ❌ Using "should" for mandatory requirements
- ❌ Using quality adverbs without numbers ("fast," "easy")
- ❌ Writing in passive voice
- ❌ Using vague language ("some," "many," "few")
- ❌ Including opinions instead of facts

### Structure Mistakes

- ❌ Missing problem statement
- ❌ No glossary for domain terms
- ❌ Missing diagrams for complex systems
- ❌ No version history
- ❌ Requirements that can't be verified

### Content Mistakes

- ❌ Non-atomic requirements (multiple things in one)
- ❌ Missing error handling specifications
- ❌ No performance benchmarks
- ❌ Undefined data constraints
- ❌ Missing security requirements

### Maintenance Mistakes

- ❌ Documentation not updated with code
- ❌ Dead documentation for deleted features
- ❌ Duplicated content instead of linking
- ❌ No decision rationale
- ❌ Missing assumptions

### Visual Design Mistakes

- ❌ Chartjunk (3D effects, shadows, decorations)
- ❌ Distorted scales to exaggerate differences
- ❌ Too many elements in one diagram (cognitive overload)
- ❌ Inconsistent symbols/icons throughout document
- ❌ Centered body text (should be left-aligned)
- ❌ Poor color contrast (accessibility issues)
- ❌ No visual hierarchy (all headings same size)
- ❌ Diagrams requiring extensive explanation
- ❌ Random placement of elements (no alignment)
- ❌ Everything same color (no contrast)
- ❌ Cramped layout (no white space)
- ❌ Missing context in charts (no baselines)
- ❌ Using areas to compare linear numbers
- ❌ Decorative arrows (not showing real flow)
- ❌ Too many font types in one diagram

### Architecture Diagramming Mistakes

- ❌ Mystery box diagrams (unclear names, no responsibilities)
- ❌ Mixing abstraction levels (database + class in same diagram)
- ❌ All lines same style (no sync/async distinction)
- ❌ Spaghetti diagrams (too many crossing lines)
- ❌ No legend (assuming reader knows symbols)
- ❌ Unlabeled connections (no protocols indicated)
- ❌ Missing failure points (no resilience shown)
- ❌ Outdated diagrams (more dangerous than no diagram)
- ❌ Jumping to code details without context diagram
- ❌ No visual boundaries for bounded contexts
- ❌ Random colors (no meaning)
- ❌ Too many components in one diagram (50+)

### Data Modeling Mistakes

- ❌ Custom notation (not standard ERD)
- ❌ Entities as verbs ("Invoicing" instead of "Invoice")
- ❌ Unclear cardinality (ambiguous relationships)
- ❌ Direct M:N relationships (not decomposed)
- ❌ Unclear optionality (no solid/dashed distinction)
- ❌ Unlabeled relationships (no verb phrases)
- ❌ Diagonal spaghetti (not orthogonal layout)
- ❌ Entity soup (too many tables in one diagram)
- ❌ Unclear foreign keys
- ❌ Plural table names ("Customers" instead of "Customer")
- ❌ Mixed logical and physical in same diagram
- ❌ Derived attributes in model
- ❌ Cramped text (poor information density)
- ❌ No data type definitions in physical model

### Information Architecture Mistakes

- ❌ Dense text blocks (not scannable)
- ❌ Unclear user flows (no step-by-step)
- ❌ High-fidelity before structure validation
- ❌ Technical jargon in labels
- ❌ No empty/error states shown
- ❌ Rectangles for decisions (should be diamonds)
- ❌ Random flow directions
- ❌ Dead ends in flow diagrams
- ❌ No exit points documented
- ❌ Too many clicks (unoptimized paths)
- ❌ Inconsistent iconography
- ❌ Low color contrast (accessibility issues)
- ❌ No platform adaptability shown

### Logical Structure Mistakes

- ❌ Main idea at end (should be first)
- ❌ Bottom-up structure (should be pyramid)
- ❌ Lists of 10+ items (should be 3-5)
- ❌ Random order (no logical sequence)
- ❌ Overlapping sections (not MECE)
- ❌ Redundant paragraphs
- ❌ Text descriptions for complex relationships (should be graphics)
- ❌ Abrupt transitions between sections
- ❌ Everything bolded (no emphasis)
- ❌ Generic TOC (doesn't tell story)
- ❌ Mixed abstraction levels in same section
- ❌ Flat structure (no indentation/hierarchy)
- ❌ Mixed categories in lists
- ❌ Verbose explanations (should be brief)
- ❌ No section conclusions
- ❌ Uneven document symmetry
- ❌ All diagrams at end (should be near text)
- ❌ Vague ending (no clear next steps)

---

**Remember:** A great technical specification is clear, complete, verifiable, maintainable, visually structured, logically organized, and architecturally sound. The visual design and logical structure determine whether the team will read the document or ignore it. Revise and rewrite until it shines.
